I. SUMMARY                                                        9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The cross section data file for neutron reactions with 239U    9240 1451
has been evaluated over the incident neutron energy range from    9240 1451
10-5 eV to 30 MeV.  This work utilizes results from a new         9240 1451
theoretical study, which includes a systematic analysis of        9240 1451
first-chance fission data from 232,233,234,235,236,238U + n       9240 1451
reactions.                                                        9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   Details of the present analysis are given in the sections      9240 1451
that follow.  Some general features of the work are:              9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
1.  The ENDF/B-VI n + 237U resonance parameters were adopted for  9240 1451
n + 239U at neutron energies below 10 keV, as modified in the Los 9240 1451
Alamos 1998 evaluation of n + 237U reactions (Yo98).  The         9240 1451
resonance analysis was suitably joined with the present analysis  9240 1451
at 10 keV.                                                        9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
2.  A systematic analysis was performed of experimental fission   9240 1451
and radiative capture cross section data for uranium isotopes     9240 1451
between 232U and 238U.  An isospin-dependent coupled-channel      9240 1451
optical model potential was developed for the uranium isotopes    9240 1451
and was used to calculate the n + 239U neutron total cross        9240 1451
section, elastic and inelastic scattering cross sections,         9240 1451
elastic scattering angular distributions, and reaction cross      9240 1451
sections.  Transmission coefficients were obtained from the       9240 1451
optical model for theoretical calculations with reaction theory   9240 1451
codes.                                                            9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
3.  Photon prod. and the fission neutron spectra were taken from  9240 1451
the existing ENDF/B-VI evaluation for n + 237U reactions.         9240 1451
Nubar was estimated from systematics.                             9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
II.  THEORETICAL ANALYSIS                                         9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
  The basic approach followed was to fit the available            9240 1451
experimental data for (n,f), (n,g), (n,xn), and other reactions   9240 1451
for the stable uranium isotopes using nuclear models, and to      9240 1451
then use reasonable extrapolations of the parameters to infer     9240 1451
cross sections for 239U.  To perform the analysis, we utilized    9240 1451
the Hauser-Feshbach reaction theory code COMNUC, the Hauser-      9240 1451
Feshbach/preequilibrium reaction theory code GNASH, and the       9240 1451
coupled-channels optical model code ECIS.                         9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
    A.  Optical Model                                             9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The deformed optical model potential was obtained by           9240 1451
considering several coupled-channel parameterizations developed   9240 1451
from n + 235,238U and 239Pu experimental data , several of which  9240 1451
were used in ENDF/B-VI evaluations.  The Harwell potential by     9240 1451
Madland and Young (Ma78), the Bruyeres-le-Chatel (BRC) potential  9240 1451
by Lagrange (Ha82), and a modified version of the BRC potential   9240 1451
by Arthur and Young (Yo88, Yo92a) were examined.  Isospin         9240 1451
corrections were applied to all the potentials to adapt them for  9240 1451
the various U isotopes.  Corrections from the measured to the     9240 1451
unmeasured cases were made in the deformation parameters b2 and   9240 1451
b4, using a simple model by D. Madland to calculate deformation   9240 1451
parameters for targets without experimental information from      9240 1451
deformations given in the extensive Nix-Moller mass analysis.     9240 1451
For the optical model potential, we chose to use an isospin       9240 1451
version of the BRC potential (Ha82), which was inferred from      9240 1451
Lagrange's results for individual nuclides.  The lowest three     9240 1451
members of the 5/2+ ground state rotational band were included    9240 1451
in the calculations, that is, the 7/2+ and 9/2+ states at Ex =    9240 1451
42.5 and 98.6 keV were coupled with the 5/2+ ground state.  All   9240 1451
of the potentials considered gave total and reaction cross        9240 1451
sections that were reasonably consistent, so the selection was    9240 1451
based mainly on the fact that the BRC potential gave better       9240 1451
agreement with fission cross sections for odd U isotopes          9240 1451
(233,235U) at lower energies.                                     9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   B.  Reaction Theory Calculations                               9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The Hauser-Feshbach statistical calculations were performed    9240 1451
with the COMNUC (Du70) and GNASH (Yo92b) codes.  Both codes       9240 1451
include a double-humped fission barrier model, using uncoupled    9240 1451
oscillators for the barrier representation in GNASH and coupled   9240 1451
or uncoupled oscillators in COMNUC, as described by Arthur        9240 1451
(Ar82).  The COMNUC calculations include the possibility of       9240 1451
width-fluctuation corrections and corrections for class II        9240 1451
fluctuations, which are needed at lower energies, whereas GNASH   9240 1451
provides the preequilibrium corrections that are required at      9240 1451
higher energies.  Accordingly, COMNUC was used in the             9240 1451
calculations below about 0.5 MeV, utilizing a non-resonant model  9240 1451
and including class II fluctuations, and the GNASH code was       9240 1451
employed at higher energies using two uncoupled oscillators in    9240 1451
the fission calculations.                                         9240 1451
   Each compound nucleus formed in the calculations is permitted  9240 1451
to decay through the fission channel, by neutron emission, and    9240 1451
by gamma-ray emission.  Neutron transmission coefficients for     9240 1451
the Hauser-Feshbach calculations are obtained from the coupled-   9240 1451
channel optical model.  Gamma ray transmission coefficients are   9240 1451
obtained from gamma-ray strength functions calculated with the    9240 1451
generalized Lorentzian model of Kopecky and Uhl (Ko90).           9240 1451
Transmission coefficients for fission are calculated from the     9240 1451
fission model summarized here and detailed in Yo92b.              9240 1451
   Gilbert and Cameron (Gi70) phenomenological level density      9240 1451
functions were used to represent continuum levels at ground-      9240 1451
state deformations, appropriately matched to available            9240 1451
experimental structure data at lower excitation energies.         9240 1451
Multiplicative factors were applied to the level density          9240 1451
functions to account for enhancements in the fission transition   9240 1451
state densities at the fission barriers due to increased          9240 1451
asymmetry conditions, and the continuum level densities were      9240 1451
matched to the discrete fission transition states at each         9240 1451
barrier.  The discrete fission transition state spectra were      9240 1451
calculated from bandhead information taken from calculations and  9240 1451
compilations by Britt (Br82).                                     9240 1451
   Initial values of fission barrier parameters were taken from   9240 1451
the work of Britt (Br82,Ba74), and we used default level density  9240 1451
parameters of Gilbert and Cameron for all ground state nuclei.    9240 1451
We only modified the Britt-Back parameters in very simple ways    9240 1451
in order to facilitate extrapolation of the parameters.  Our      9240 1451
modifications were limited to minor adjustments of the fission    9240 1451
barrier heights, the pairing energy at the fission barriers       9240 1451
(although we usually used the Gilbert-Cameron values), and the    9240 1451
level matching of the temperature region of the continuum level   9240 1451
densities at the fission saddles.                                 9240 1451
   We fit the experimental (n,f) and (n,g) cross sections for     9240 1451
all stable isotopes over the energy region of first-chance        9240 1451
fission using the COMNUC model code.  Experimental data exists    9240 1451
for targets of 232U, 233U, 234U, 235U, 236U, and 238U, which      9240 1451
allowed us to infer fission barrier parameters and gamma-ray      9240 1451
strength functions for the compound systems of 233U, 234U, 235U,  9240 1451
236U, 237U, and 239U.  Using the parameters determined from the   9240 1451
first-chance fission fitting without modification, we performed   9240 1451
GNASH calculations over the entire energy region of each target   9240 1451
nucleus.  We carried the calculations to 30 MeV, which involve    9240 1451
first-, second-, third-, fourth-, and fifth-chance fission        9240 1451
processes.   These comparisons provide a necessary test of the    9240 1451
reliability of our calculations, in that no adjustments are made  9240 1451
past the first-chance fission results.                            9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
III.  DESCRIPTION OF EVALUATED DATA BASE                          9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   A.  Total Cross Section                                        9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The evaluated total cross section below 10 keV is obtained     9240 1451
from the n + 237U resonance parameter evaluation in ENDF/B-VI,    9240 1451
as modified in a recent Los Alamos evaluation (Yo98).  From 10    9240 1451
keV to 30 MeV, the coupled-channel deformed optical model         9240 1451
calculations described above are used directly.                   9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   B.  Elastic Cross Section                                      9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The elastic cross section at all energies is obtained from     9240 1451
the difference of the total and nonelastic cross sections.        9240 1451
Below 10 keV it comes from the resonance parameters and at        9240 1451
higher energies it is determined by the coupled-channel optical   9240 1451
model calculations.  Angular distributions for elastic neutrons   9240 1451
were obtained at all energies from the ECIS coupled-channel       9240 1451
calculations combined with the COMNUC compound-elastic            9240 1451
calculations (see above) and are given as Legendre expansions.    9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   C.  Fission Cross Section                                      9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The fission cross section is calculated from the resonance     9240 1451
parameters below 10 keV, as described earlier.  At higher         9240 1451
energies the fission cross section is based on the theoretical    9240 1451
analysis described above.                                         9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   D.  Radiative Capture Cross Section                            9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   Below 10 keV, the capture cross section is based on the        9240 1451
resonance parameters.  At higher energies the cross section is    9240 1451
calculated using the generalized Lorentzian model of Ko90.  The   9240 1451
normalization of the strength function was set by requiring the   9240 1451
calculated (n,g) cross section be consistent with measured        9240 1451
values for 235U, similar to our n + 237U evaluation               9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   E.  Inelastic Neutron Cross Sections                           9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   Discrete (n,n') cross sections are included for the lowest 11  9240 1451
excited states of 239U.  The first and second excited states are  9240 1451
members of the K = 5/2 ground-state rotational band and include   9240 1451
coupled-channel as well as compound nucleus contributions from th 9240 1451
COMNUC calculations.  The remaining discrete-state cross sections 9240 1451
through the 11th excited state are combinations of compound nucle 9240 1451
and preequilibrium contributions and were calculated with the GNA 9240 1451
code.  Angular distributions for these discrete inelastic neutron 9240 1451
are appropriate combinations of the compound nucleus, direct      9240 1451
reaction, and preequilibrium contributions and are represented by 9240 1451
Legendre expansions.  The higher (n,n') states (MT=62-86) are     9240 1451
assumed grouped collective levels based on direct-reaction        9240 1451
calculations for 238U with the ECIS96 code, with the assumption   9240 1451
that similar states exist for 239U.  The angular distributions of 9240 1451
all excited levels are represented by Legendre expansions.        9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The inelastic data for compound nucleus reactions correspondin 9240 1451
to excitation energies in 239U above 0.373 MeV are given as energ 9240 1451
angle correlated continuous spectra and were calculated with the  9240 1451
GNASH code.  The results are given in File 6 of the ENDF/B-       9240 1451
formatted evaluation (ENDF-6 format) and utilize systematics by   9240 1451
Kalbach (Ka88) for angular distribution information, parameterize 9240 1451
in terms of preequilibrium ratios calculated in GNASH.  These     9240 1451
compound-nucleus contributions overlap the assumed direct reactio 9240 1451
contributions for MT=62-86.                                       9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   F.  Cross Sections for 239U(n,xn) Reactions                    9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The 239U(n,2n), (n,3n), and (n,4n) cross sections result       9240 1451
entirely from the theoretical analysis and GNASH calculations.    9240 1451
   Energy-angle correlated distributions are given for all the    9240 1451
239U(n,xn) reactions, making use of Kalbach's systematics (Ka88)  9240 1451
and the ENDF/B-6 File 6 representation.                           9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   G.  Nubar                                                      9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The evaluation of delayed nubar were carried over directly     9240 1451
from the ENDF/B-VI evaluation of 237U.  The prompt nubar          9240 1451
evaluation is based on the systematics of Manero and Konshin      9240 1451
(Ma72), updated using experimental values for targets of 235U     9240 1451
and 238U .                                                        9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   H.  Fission Neutron Spectra                                    9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The fission neutron spectra in the revised evaluation is also  9240 1451
carried over directly from the 237U evaluation in ENDF/B-VI.  A   9240 1451
maxwellian representation is used for the spectrum shape, with    9240 1451
energy-dependent temperature parameters based on systematics.     9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
IV.  CONCLUSIONS                                                  9240 1451
                                                                  9240 1451
   The new analysis of n + 239U nuclear data should provide a     9240 1451
reasonable representation of most reactions over the incident     9240 1451
energy range 10 keV to 30 MeV.  This evaluation is regarded as    9240 1451
preliminary until the results of our assumptions regarding the    9240 1451
fission cross section can be further assessed.  Additionally,     9240 1451
improvements to the evaluations of nubar and the fission neutron  9240 1451
spectra using the Madland-Nix approach will be considered in the  9240 1451
future.                                                           9240 1451
